data.content:
xUnit has no setup/teardown attributes. Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture |

Converted code:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once and injects it into the constructor. It's disposed after all tests in the class complete.
- **Constructor** — xUnit creates a new class instance per test, so the constructor is your per-test setup.
- **`Assert.Equal(expected, actual)`** — note the argument order is reversed from NUnit's `Is.EqualTo`.
